\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 Dam Dam}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 By Sana Nassari}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 To Arundhati Roy}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u160}}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 The news had disturbed everyone. I was playing with my friends in the street. In my childhood. A man knocked on our neighbour\uc0{\u8217}s door. Aramies\uc0{\u8217} house. Aramies disturbance house.\uc0{\u160}Mrs Aramy, chubby and smiling, appeared in front of the man. I could not hear the man. He seemed very upset, but not as upset as Mrs Aramy in a few second.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 The news was revealed quietly in a single short sentence, like all bad news, probably. Mrs Aramy was staring at the man. Her decision to choose how to react only took a second. Extremely short second to decide to draw her hands to her neck. She pulled two lapels of the collar of her cotton long dress to opposite sides. Her scream last as long as the collar took to be torn from top to the bottom of the dress. Mr Aramy rushed to the door. Now, his wife was sitting on the ground, crying and weeping. Mr Aramy leaned to the door. Neighbours in their pyjamas and chadors gathered around the mourner old man and woman. Amidst the crowd of people\uc0{\u8217}s legs, I reached my mum\uc0{\u8217}s chador and stuck his warm thigh. My mum\uc0{\u8217}s body was shaking bit by bit. I raised my head. Her face was wrinkled. She was crying.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 Dam Dam.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 He was wearing an army uniform and definitely heading their home. He was on leave. It was the first and the last time that the idea of such ridiculous trouble making came to my mind. It was noon sharp. I escaped from the nap to press one of the neighbours\uc0{\u8217} ring and run. The ring of Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s house as they did not have any children at my age, so there would not be any fight afterwards. I could not reach the ring. I had not thought of the height of the ring. I found a dry and narrow branch from the dry flower bed. The man was coming from the end of the street. It was useless. The branch was too short and narrow. The man was behind me. I should not run. Running was planned to happen after ringing.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u160}}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u8211}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160} Can\uc0{\u8217}t you reach the ring, darling?}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 I turned back. It was Mehran. Mehran was wearing an army uniform and he definitely was heading their house. He was on leave. His forehead was covered with shining drops of sweat. It was a hot sunny day. Looking at Mehran, I kept my head up. I was struck dumb. My neck was aching. Mehran went to the door. His khaki uniform, socked with sweat, was sticking to his back. I saw his hand which was moving toward the ring(bell?). I wished the power go off so the ring does not sound but the monotonous hum of coolers that came from all yards until the very last moment ensured me that it will not happen. Mehran\uc0{\u8217}s index finger went to the doorbell and pressed the bottom. The loud ding dong filled my ears. I threw the branch and ran off.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 I could imagine that Mehran had been left open-mouthed and Mr Kamaly with lots of beards had opened the door and faced an open-mouthed soldier Mehran who had not any excuse for his troubling especially on that such a noon sharp. I had left our door open. I rushed into the yard and closed the door. I was panting. What if Mehran directly comes to our place and tell everything to my parents? I pricked up my ears and waited. I heard the unencumbered steps of Mehran\uc0{\u8217}s combat boots that stopped at their door. Then the ding dong of their doorbell. Once. Ding dong. Twice. The sound of their hall entrance. The sound of Mrs Aramy wearing her sandals and shuffling along the yard to the door.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u8211}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160} Who is it?}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 The door was opened. I could hear Mrs Aramy\uc0{\u8217}s scream of joy and smack of her lips kissing Mehran.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u8211}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160} Welcome my dearest. You didn\uc0{\u8217}t tell me that you have days off. I would give my life for yours, my beloved Mehran.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 The astonished voice of Mehran said, \uc0{\u8220}Mum, Mr Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s daughter has grown up!\uc0{\u8221}}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 And without any reason, I thought when I reached the age of Mr Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s daughter I would get engaged with an astonished soldier who rang our doorbell without any excuse and then apologised and headed their house.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u160}}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 Dam dam.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 Mr Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s daughter, barefoot, ran to the crowd. Everyone stepped aside so that Mrs Aramy and Mr Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s daughter can hug each other. The chador of the daughter}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 Mr Kamaly slid and fell on her shoulders. Her hair was black and glossy. Without hair claw or clips, Flowing, on her shoulders. My mum\uc0{\u8217}s weeping raised a bit. They were sitting on the ground; Mrs Aramy without any intention to close her torn-up collar and Mr Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s daughter without any intention to cover her hair from men. Mr Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s daughter was slapping on both sides of her own face and repeating: Mehran, Mehran, Mehran, Mehran. And I thought when I reached the age of Mr Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s daughter I would not get engaged with an astonished soldier who rang our doorbell without any excuse and then apologised and headed their house. Because without any doubt my fianc\uc0{\u233} will sink, be a martyr and finally die.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 Mehran sank, martyred and finally died in the Arvand river.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u160}}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 Dam dam}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 That night the street was decorated with colourful lights and Mehran\uc0{\u8217}s photo, with some modification and clearly prettier than himself was put on a table in front of their house for his memorial. It seemed that all people of the town were gathered in our street. mourning song was playing from the loudspeakers. Amidst the crowd, cries, teas and dates, I took myself to Aramies. I was looking for my mum but the compression of black worn hips did not let me see the faces. Like an ant that can find its way, I took myself to the door of Mehran\uc0{\u8217}s room. The doorknob was too form for me. I kept it tight with my hands and dangled from it. Door opened. Mehran\uc0{\u8217}s bedroom was the only peaceful place in the house. Six young girls were sitting there, quietly making confetti. Mehran\uc0{\u8217}s sister, who recently was married, was among the girls. Tearing silently and cutting the colourful papers. I was afraid of being asked to leave the room but none of the girls cared about me. I sat mutely beside the door and watched them cutting the shining papers, unaware that on this sad occasion these happy colourful ornaments tomorrow will increase the weeping and sorrows, reminds everyone of the never-happened wedding of Mehran and Mr Kamaly\uc0{\u8217}s daughter.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u160}}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 The day after that, it was almost noon when I woke up. No one was around. I could hear a hum from outside. I opened the front door. There was pandemonium. Women and men were standing in the street. In a circular\uc0{\u8230} They were awaiting the beginning of an event. I could not go to the centre of the people through the legs. Suddenly someone grabbed me from the armpit and picked me up. It was a young man who I knew. A relative to my dad. He sat me on his shoulders.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u8211}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160}\uc0{\u160} Can you see darling?}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 I trembled when I heard the word darling.}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 \uc0{\u8220}Can\uc0{\u8217}t you reach the ring, darling?\uc0{\u8221}}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 I could see. The young boys were made the internal ring of the crowd. Some instruments like drums were hung from their necks. Everyone was wearing black. A man who was standing at the centre of the circle was holding a long stick at the top of which a large red flag was hung. Everyone was silent. The man roared: Ya Husayn! The crowd answered: Ya Ali!}}\par
\pard\nowidctlpar {{\cf0\f0 The man waved the flag above the crowd and the ritual began. The silk cloth slid softly in the air, waved and snuggled around the stick. Then again with the next move separated from the stick and passed over our heads. Flags were going and coming back in the sky over my head; red, blue, red, blue, red.}}\par
